{{Infobox language |name = Akhvakh |nativename = Ашвaлъи мицIи |states = [[Russia]], [[Azerbaijan]] |region = Southern [[Dagestan]], northern Azerbaijan |ethnicity=[[Akhvakh people|Akhvakh]] |speakers = 210 in Dagestan |date = 2010 census |ref=e18 |familycolor = Caucasian |fam1 = [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]] |fam2 = [[Avar–Andic languages|Avar–Andic]] |fam3 = [[Andic languages|Andic]] |fam4 = Akhvakh–Tindi |iso3 = akv |glotto=akhv1239 |glottorefname=Akhvakh }}
The '''Akhvakh language''' (also spelled ''Axvax, Akhwakh'') is a [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian language]] from the [[Avar–Andic languages|Avar–Andic branch]]. Ethnologue lists 6500 speakers,<ref name="Ethnologue">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=akv Ethnologue entry for Akhvakh, which also mentions its divergent dialects]</ref> but Magomedova and Abulaeva (2007) list 20,000 speakers of the language. Akhvakh has several dialects, though sources do not agree on the number. Ethnologue lists [[Kaxib dialect|Kaxib]], [[Northern Akhvakh]] and [[Southern Akhvakh]] (which can be further subdivided into the [[Tlyanub dialect|Tlyanub]] and [[Tsegob dialect|Tsegob]] subdialects<ref name="Redbook">[http://www.eki.ee/books/redbook/akhvakhs.shtml The peoples of the Red Book: Akhvakhs]</ref>). Creissels (2010) lists Northern Akhvakh and three dialects of Southern Akhvakh (Cegob, Tljanub, and Ratlub).
A few publications have been made in the Akhvakh language{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}, but for the most part speakers of Akhvakh have adopted [[Avar language|Avar]] as their literary language.
