* {{IPA|/m, mʲ, p, pʲ, b, bʲ, w, wʲ/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]],{{fix|text=are /w, wʲ/ bilabial or labialized velar?|date=April 2015}} whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=605}}
* {{IPA|/n, nʲ, l, r, rʲ/}} are alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n}}, nʲ, {{IPA link|l}}, {{IPA link|r}}, rʲ]}}, whereas {{IPA|/t, d, t͡s, s, z/}} are dental {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}, {{IPA link|t̪͡s̪}}, {{IPA link|s̪}}, {{IPA link|z̪}}]}}.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=605}}
* {{IPA|/t͡ʃ, ʃ, ʒ/}} have been variously transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|t͡ʃ, ʃ, ʒ}}}}{{sfnp|Hannusch|1988}}{{sfnp|Stone|2002}} and {{angle bracket|{{IPA|t͡ʂ, ʂ, ʐ}}}}.{{sfnp|Zygis|2003}} Their actual phonetic realization is flat postalveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t͡ʂ|t͡ʃ˖}}, {{IPA link|ʂ|ʃ˖}}, {{IPA link|ʐ|ʒ˖}}]}}<ref>This transcription follows {{Harvcoltxt|Laver|1994|pp=251–252}}. Other scholars may transcribe these sounds differently.</ref> in all of the Lower Sorbian-speaking area. This is unlike in standard Upper Sorbian, where these are [[Palato-alveolar consonant|palato-alveolar]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t͡ʃ}}, {{IPA link|ʃ}}, {{IPA link|ʒ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Zygis|2003|pp=180–181, 190–191}}{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=40–41}}
* {{IPA|/h/}} is voiceless {{IPAblink|h}}, unlike Upper Sorbian, where it is voiced {{IPAblink|ɦ}}.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|pp=600, 605}}{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=43, 46}}

====Final devoicing and assimilation====
Lower Sorbian has both [[final devoicing]] and regressive [[phonation|voicing]] [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilation]]:{{sfnp|Hannusch|1998|p=12}} 
*''dub'' {{IPA|/dub/}} "oak" is pronounced {{IPA|[dup]}}
*''susedka'' {{IPA|/ˈsusedka/}} "(female) neighbor" is pronounced {{IPA|[ˈsusetka]}}
*''licba'' {{IPA|/ˈlit͡sba/}} "number" is pronounced {{IPA|[ˈlʲid͡zba]}}

The hard postalveolar fricative {{IPA|/ʃ/}} is assimilated to {{IPA|[ɕ]}} before {{IPA|/t͡ɕ/}}:{{sfnp|Hannusch|1998|p=13}}
*''šćit'' {{IPA|/ʃt͡ɕit/}} "protection" is pronounced {{IPA|[ɕt͡ɕit]}}

===Vowels===
The vowel inventory of Lower Sorbian is exactly the same as that of Upper Sorbian.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=600}} It is also very similar to the vowel inventory of [[Slovene language|Slovene]].

