{{Infobox writer | name = Marja-Liisa Orvokki Vartio | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = PaavoHaavikko-MLVartio-1960.jpg | caption = With author Paavo Haavikko }}
'''Marja-Liisa Orvokki Vartio''' (née '''Sairanen''', 1955-1966 Haavikko; 11 September 1924 [[Sääminki]], [[Finland]] – 17 June 1966 [[Savonlinna]], Finland) was a Finnish poet and prose writer. Her writing career was short but influential. She was one of the leading modernist writers in Finland.<ref name="HUM">{{cite web |url=http://375humanistia.helsinki.fi/en/humanists/marja-liisa-vartio |title=Marja-Liisa Vartio |last= Sjöblom |first=Tom |date= |website=375 humanists |publisher=University of Helsinki |access-date=23 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref>
She studied art history and modern literature in University of Helsinki. She married an art dealer in 1945 and was introduced into Helsinki’s writing and artistic circles. Her first collection s of poetry were published in 1952. In 1955 she married writer [[Paavo Haavikko]]. Around that time she started to write prose.<ref name="HUM2">{{cite web |url=http://375humanistia.helsinki.fi/en/marja-liisa-vartio/reshaping-finnish-prose |title=Reshaping Finnish Prose |last= Sjöblom |first=Tom |date= |website=375 humanists |publisher=University of Helsinki |access-date=23 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref>
Vartio published nine works of prose and poetry. Her works describe how the world changed in the twentieth century and the influence of this on human beings, especially on women. In her poetry she used folk literature as an inspiration. One of her novels, ''Hänen olivat linnut'' (The Parson’s Widow) was published after her death. It tells about an old woman and her maid.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.schwob-books.eu/author/90/marja-liisa-vartio |title=Marja-Liisa Vartio |website=Schwob |access-date=23 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref> The novel is considered Vartio's most central work.<ref name="HUM2"/>
